it's taquitos or cabrito, mescal or pozole, the answer will be a tasty one. <strong>Gustavo Arellano</strong> is so helpful, he even points out a good place to sample Mexican food in the UK","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-06-20T04:30:59Z","body":"<figure data-media-id='gu-image-411291927'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Pix/pictures/2013/6/12/1371052226577/Ask-a-Mexican-logo-003.jpg' alt='Ask a Mexican logo' width='140' height='130' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Image: Mark Dancey</figcaption></figure><p><strong>Dear Mexican …</strong></p><p><strong>I'm a Brit who's travelling to New Mexico and Texas this summer. We love our Tex-Mex in England – all that chilli and yellow cheese! So where can I get the good stuff?</strong><br /><em>The Boy with the Nachos in His Side</em></p><p>You're not going to find much chilli and yellow cheese in New Mexico (or even in Texas – the two states have about as much in common as Doctor Who and Star Wars). New Mexico is most famous for its <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hatch_chile\" title=\"\">hatch chillies</a>: fulsome, fleshy peppers from the southern part of the \"Land of Enchantment\" that the locals either eat whole, or grill and put inside cheeseburgers – the <a href=\"http://lotaburger.com/\" title=\"\">Blake's Lotaburger</a> chain is famous for its version – or turn into a stew. New Mexico's Mexican food is unique because it dates back to the days of the Spanish conquistadors, back when you Brits were still eating each other at Jamestown.</p><p>You should think of Texas, meanwhile, as a large, unwieldy country of countries with edible brimstone (salsa) the sole unifier. Since you want to visit New Mexico as well, you'll probably only be able to travel via El Paso – and stop at Chico's Tacos (5305 Montana Avenue, +1 915 772 7777, no website) and order the rolled tacos – what we call taquitos.</p><p>In case you travel elsewhere in Texas, here's a brief Tex-Mex primer: in San Antonio, the natives eat puffy tacos, which look like a Cornish pasty inflated to its golden, crispy extreme. South Texas is famous for its <em>barbacoa</em> (a slow-roasted cow's head) and <em>cabrito</em> (slow-roasted kid – as in the goat, not a small child). Texas also is the land of nachos, so do me a favour, Boy, remind them that they stole the idea of vile yellow goop poured over crunchy trash from your Welsh rarebit.</p><p><strong>Do we have authentic Mexican food in the UK?</strong><br /><em>Finito Benito's</em></p><p>Yes, and no. My friends who have travelled across the pond always return with horror stories about the Mexican food there, and all agree with <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/cifamerica/2011/feb/04/mexico-top-gear\" title=\"\">the Top Gear <em>pendejos</em></a> – Mexican food in Britain <em>is</em> refried sick. But it's still Mexican food. See, all tacos are created equal but some tacos are more equal than others. When people ask about \"authentic\" food, they mean regional Mexican specialities that haven't achieved widespread popularity. A good place to try these dishes in the UK is at one of <a href=\"http://wahaca.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Wahaca</a>'s eight London restaurants. Its <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mezcal\" title=\"\"><em>mescal</em></a> comes from Mexico's rural regions, <em>tinga</em> is a chicken preparation from Mexico City, and <em>pibil</em> (slow-roasted pork) is the pride and joy of the Yucatan.</p><p><strong>If you could only have one Mexican meal in Texas or New Mexico, what would it be and where would you have it?</strong><br /><em>This Sporting Salsa Life </em></p><p>That's like a Mexican asking a Brit which Mr Bean bit is his favourite. Instead of directing you to the big cities, I'm throwing a rural beauty your way: Chope's Bar and Cafe in La Mesa, New Mexico (16145 New Mexico 28, +1 575 233 3420). It's a 40-minute drive west from El Paso but worth the trek. Chope's is a tiny restaurant selling some of the best <em>pozol</em>e (a stew made from local pork and chillis harvested from the Mesilla valley, in which La Mesa is situated) in the state, and its sister bar is right next door, a heaven for lushes of all nationalities. Make sure to end your La Mesa adventure with a pecan-based dessert, as the scenic drive you'll take goes through the largest pecan grove in the world.</p><p><strong>Ask A Mexican at themexican @</strong><a href=\"http://www.gustavoarellano.net/\" title=\"\"><strong>askamexican.net</strong></a><strong>, follow him on Twitter </strong><a href=\"https://twitter.com/GustavoArellano\" title=\"\"><strong>@gustavoarellano</strong></a><strong> or ask a video question at </strong><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/askamexicano\" title=\"\"><strong>youtube.com/askamexicano</strong></a></p><p>• <strong>For more information on holidays in the USA, visit </strong><a href=\"http://www.discoveramerica.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>DiscoverAmerica.com</strong></a></p>","headline":"Tex-Mex food for thought with ¡Ask a Mexican!","trailText":"<p>¡Ask a Mexican! your US food and drink questions, and whether it's taquitos, cabrito, mescal or pozole, the answer will be a tasty one, says <strong>Gustavo Arellano</strong></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"2","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Pix/pictures/2013/6/12/1371052002445/Southwestern-style-bowl-o-003.jpg","wordcount":"611","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"410627468","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"7704242","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Gustavo Arellano","newspaperEditionDate":"2013-06-22T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1921495","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2013-06-24T23:10:16Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/2013/jun/22/tex-mex-food-ask-a-mexican","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/2013/jun/22/tex-mex-food-ask-a-mexican","tags":[{"id":"travel/travelfoodanddrink","webTitle":"Food and drink","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/travelfoodanddrink","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/travelfoodanddrink","references":[]},{"id":"travel/new-mexico","webTitle":"New Mexico","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/new-mexico","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/new-mexico","references":[]},{"id":"travel/texas","webTitle":"Texas","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/texas","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/texas","references":[]},{"id":"travel/series/road-trips-usa-texas-and-new-mexico","webTitle":"Road trips USA: Texas and New Mexico","type":"series","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/series/road-trips-usa-texas-and-new-mexico","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/series/road-trips-usa-texas-and-new-mexico","references":[]},{"id":"travel/usa","webTitle":"United States","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/usa","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/usa","references":[]},{"id":"travel/northandcentralamerica","webTitle":"North and Central America","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/northandcentralamerica","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/northandcentralamerica","references":[]},{"id":"travel/travel","webTitle":"Travel","type":"keyword","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/travel/travel","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/travel/travel","references":[]},{"id":"lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","webTitle":"Food & drink","type":"keyword","sectionId"